    {
      "type": "context",
      "agent": "user",
      "content": "# ARCHITECT PLAN OVERVIEW\n**Plan**: Implement human-like navigation behavior during crawl with session rotation, rate limiting, and intelligent retry.\n**Description**: Add pre-navigation hooks (random delay, viewport, cookie consent) and post-navigation hooks (progressive scroll, mouse emulation, wait). Configure session pool with maxPoolSize 5, set maxConcurrency to 1-2, enable maxRequestRetries 3 with exponential backoff and implement proxy rotation on retry. Update the integration test to align with new crawler options and optionally extend the input schema to expose configurable parameters.\n## All Steps\n1. **Add pre-navigation hooks (delay, viewport, cookie consent)**: ## Goal\nExtend the existing `preNavigationHooks` array in `src/main.ts` to add human-like delays and cookie consent handling before page navigation, simulating real user behavior.\n\n## Task Type\nCode modification — add logic to an existing hook array.\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\n- **File**: `src/main.ts` (lines ~79-91 currently define a `preNavigationHooks` array with a single hook that blocks trackers via `BLOCKED_PATTERNS`).\n- **Existing viewport**: `launchOptions` already applies a random viewport (`getRandomViewport()`) via Camoufox. Pre-navigation can override it per page if desired, but not required.\n- **Delay mechanism**: Use `page.waitForTimeout(ms)` within hooks. Random delay between 1000-4000ms.\n- **Cookie consent**: Use `page.addInitScript` or `page.evaluate` to set `navigator.cookieEnabled` or push a consent banner click. A simple approach: use `page.evaluate(() => { document.cookie = 'cookie_consent=true; path=/'; })` — this suffices for simulation. For actual banner interaction, more complex logic may be needed, but for this step a minimal consent simulation is acceptable.\n- **Imports**: No new imports needed; `page` is the Playwright `Page` object provided to hooks.\n\n## Action\n1. Open `src/main.ts`.\n2. Locate the existing `preNavigationHooks` array definition (around line 79).\n3. **Insert** a new asynchronous hook function at the **beginning** of the array (before the tracker-blocking hook) that does:\n   - `await page.waitForTimeout(1000 + Math.random() * 3000);` (random 1-4 seconds)\n   - `await page.evaluate(() => { document.cookie = 'cookie_consent=true; path=/'; });` (simulate cookie consent)\n4. Optionally, for additional viewport variation, you can add `await page.setViewportSize({ width: 1920 + Math.floor(Math.random() * 200), height: 1080 + Math.floor(Math.random() * 100) });` — but note viewport is already randomized in `launchOptions`. This is not required but can be added for extra fingerprint diversity. If added, keep it after the delay.\n5. Keep the existing tracker-blocking hook unchanged.\n6. Ensure the hook signature uses `(context, page) => { ... }` (PlaywrightCrawler provides `page` as the second argument).\n\n## Reasoning\n- Random delay before each navigation mimics human hesitation (reading, thinking).\n- Cookie consent banner simulation reduces detection; many scrapers skip clicking “Accept”.\n- Viewport variety (beyond what Camoufox provides) further diversifies fingerprint.\n- Placing these before the tracker block makes them execute first.\n\n## Implementation Details\n- **Exact code to add** (replace placeholder comments with real code):\n```typescript\npreNavigationHooks: [\n    async (context, page) => {\n        // Random delay 1-4 seconds\n        await page.waitForTimeout(1000 + Math.random() * 3000);\n\n        // Simulate cookie consent by setting a consent cookie\n        await page.evaluate(() => {\n            document.cookie = 'cookie_consent=true; path=/; max-age=3600';\n        });\n\n        // Optional: random viewport (already handled in launchOptions, but can be re-set here)\n        // await page.setViewportSize({\n        //     width: 1920 + Math.floor(Math.random() * 200),\n        //     height: 1080 + Math.floor(Math.random() * 100),\n        // });\n    },\n    async (context, page) => {\n        // Existing tracker-blocking hook (preserve as is)\n        // ...\n    },\n],\n```\n- Ensure TypeScript types are satisfied; `context` is `CrawlingContext`, `page` is `Page`.\n- Keep indentation and code style consistent (4 spaces, single quotes, semicolons).\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n- `waitForTimeout` may throw if page crashes; wrap in try-catch with `log.warning` (import `log` from `apify/log`) — though timeout is minimal.\n- `page.evaluate` for cookie consent may fail on pages with strict CSP; catch error and continue (consent simulation is best-effort).\n- If the hook throws, the crawl continues to the next hook? By default, Crawlee does not abort on hook failures unless `failWithError` is set. The error will be logged. Ensure we don’t break the crawl — just log the error and let it proceed.\n\n## Validation\n- Run `npx tsc --noEmit` to verify TypeScript compilation.\n- Run `npm test` (vitest) to confirm integration test still passes (test does not use preNavigationHooks, but no regressions).\n- Optionally run `npm run start:dev` with a few start URLs and observe logs that delays occur.\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n- No new npm dependencies.\n- Assumes `page` argument is provided by Crawlee (PlaywrightCrawler).\n- The existing `preNavigationHooks` array already exists; this step only modifies it.\n\n## Constraints\n- Keep the hook count minimal (one hook for delay+consent). Do not add more than one new hook unless necessary.\n- Do not modify the tracker-blocking hook logic.\n- Stay within 60-char limit for step title.\n\n## Performance and Scalability Notes\n- Adding 1-4 second delay per page increases total crawl time, but is acceptable for human-like behavior. For large-scale runs, consider making this configurable via input schema (future step).\n- The delay is blocking; concurrency (maxConcurrency) controls parallelism, so delays only affect one request at a time.\n\n## Documentation Impact\n- No documentation changes now; later step may update README or input schema.\n\n## Diagram\n```\npreNavigationHooks:\n  [0] delay + cookie consent\n  [1] block trackers (existing)\n```\n2. **Add post-navigation hooks (scroll, mouse, wait)**: ## Goal\nAdd post-navigation hooks to simulate human-like reading behavior after each page load.\n\n## Task Type\nCode addition to existing hooks configuration in src/main.ts.\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\n- **File**: `src/main.ts` (111 lines, ESM)\n- Current structure: `preNavigationHooks` array already exists at lines 79–91 with tracker blocking logic.\n- No `postNavigationHooks` currently defined.\n- Crawler instance created with `new PlaywrightCrawler({...})` around lines 70–105.\n- `launchOptions` already includes `humanize: true` (Camoufox mouse emulation) but that only applies to browser-level actions, not scroll or wait after page load.\n- Dependencies: `@crawlee/playwright` provides `PlaywrightCrawler`; no new packages needed.\n\n## Action\nAdd a new array `postNavigationHooks` to the PlaywrightCrawler configuration options (object passed to the constructor). Each hook is an async function `(crawlingContext, request)` where `crawlingContext` provides `page` (Playwright Page).\n\nImplement the following inside the single hook:\n1. **Progressive scroll**: Use `page.evaluate()` to execute a script that scrolls the page in 10 steps with 300ms intervals (total ~3s).\n2. **Mouse emulation**: Use `page.mouse.move(x, y)` to move the mouse to random coordinates within the viewport (e.g., `Math.random() * viewportWidth`, `Math.random() * viewportHeight`). Perform 2–3 moves with 500ms delays.\n3. **Page wait**: After scroll and mouse moves, call `page.waitForTimeout(2000 + Math.random() * 3000)` to simulate reading (2–5s).\n\nPlace the new `postNavigationHooks` array immediately after the existing `preNavigationHooks` definition (i.e., after line ~91).\n\n## Reasoning\nHuman users typically scroll through content, move the mouse, and pause to read. These actions help evade bot detection by making requests appear organic. Post-navigation hooks are the appropriate Crawlee mechanism for injecting such behavior after page content is loaded.\n\n## Implementation Details\n- **Location in code**: Between the existing `preNavigationHooks` array and the crawler options object. Ensure the array is assigned to a variable or inline.\n- **Pseudo-code**:\n```ts\nconst postNavigationHooks = [\n  async ({ page }: CrawlingContext) => {\n    // Progressive scroll (10 steps, 300ms each)\n    await page.evaluate(async () => {\n      const delay = (ms: number) => new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, ms));\n      const totalHeight = document.body.scrollHeight;\n      const step = totalHeight / 10;\n      for (let i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {\n        window.scrollTo(0, i * step);\n        await delay(300);\n      }\n    });\n    // Mouse emulation\n    const viewport = page.viewportSize() || { width: 1280, height: 720 };\n    for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {\n      await page.mouse.move(\n        Math.random() * viewport.width,\n        Math.random() * viewport.height\n      );\n      await page.waitForTimeout(500);\n    }\n    // Reading wait\n    await page.waitForTimeout(2000 + Math.random() * 3000);\n  }\n];\n```\n- **Integration**: Add `postNavigationHooks` to the crawler options object alongside existing properties like `preNavigationHooks`, `launchContext`, etc.\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n- **If page is closed or detached**: The hook should catch errors from `page.evaluate`, `page.mouse.move`, etc. Wrap the entire hook body in a try-catch that logs a warning (using `log.warning`) and does not rethrow, to avoid failing the entire request.\n- **If page has no content (e.g., binary response)**: `page.evaluate` may hang or error; the same try-catch applies.\n- **If viewport is undefined**: Fallback to default (1280x720) as shown.\n- **If maxRequestRetries is set (future step)**: The hook runs before retry decisions, so it should not affect retry logic.\n\n## Validation\n1. After applying the code, verify with a test run that pages are scrolled and mouse moves occur (use `log.info` with coordinates to confirm, or observe in headed mode during dev).\n2. Ensure the existing integration test `test/main.test.ts` still passes: the test creates a crawler without hooks; we are only adding hooks to the main crawler in `src/main.ts`, not the test. The test will not be affected unless it also defines hooks.\n3. Check that the hook does not cause significant performance degradation (scroll + mouse + wait adds ~5–10s per page).\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n- Directly uses `page` object from Crawlee's `CrawlingContext`.\n- No external dependencies.\n- This step depends on the existing code structure where `preNavigationHooks` already exists; but it is independent of other steps in this plan.\n\n## Constraints\n- Must be implemented in `src/main.ts` only.\n- Must not break existing preNavigationHooks or any other crawler configuration.\n- Must follow project coding conventions: ESM, TypeScript, no console.log (use `log` from `apify/log`), semicolons, etc.\n- The hook function must be async and return a Promise.\n- Do not use any external packages; only built-in Browser API + Playwright methods.\n\n## API and Integration Impact\n- Does not change the Actor’s input/output schema.\n- Does not affect routes, dataset output, or proxy usage.\n- Only modifies the crawl behavior after each page load, making it more human-like.\n\n## Performance and Scalability Notes\n- Adds ~5–10 seconds per page (depending on scroll + mouse + wait). This increases total crawl time proportionally, but is acceptable for human-like behavior.\n- If maxConcurrency is set >1 (future step), each page will have its own post-navigation hook running in parallel; that is fine.\n\n## Documentation Impact\n- No documentation changes needed now; if later steps expose configuration options (e.g., enable/disable human behavior), documentation can be added then.\n3. **Configure session pool (useSessionPool, maxPoolSize 5)**: ## Goal\nEnable automatic session rotation in PlaywrightCrawler to provide a fresh browser fingerprint per session, reducing detection during human-like crawling.\n\n## Task Type\nModification of existing configuration in `src/main.ts`.\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\n- **File**: `src/main.ts` (approx. lines 75–105)\n- Current crawler options object includes:\n  ```ts\n  proxyConfiguration: proxyConfig,\n  maxRequestsPerCrawl,\n  launchContext: { ... },\n  preNavigationHooks: [ ... ],\n  requestHandler: router,\n  ```\n- No `useSessionPool` or `sessionPoolOptions` exist yet.\n- The crawler uses Camoufox-js with `humanize: true`, which already randomizes fingerprints at launch. Adding session pool will rotate fingerprints per session (e.g., every 5 sessions).\n- No new npm dependencies needed; `useSessionPool` and `sessionPoolOptions` are part of `@crawlee/playwright` already installed.\n\n## Action\nModify the `PlaywrightCrawler` constructor call in `src/main.ts` to add:\n- `useSessionPool: true`\n- `sessionPoolOptions: { maxPoolSize: 5 }`\n\nPlace these options near the other major configuration options (before `preNavigationHooks` or after `maxRequestsPerCrawl`). Ensure the properties are at the top level of the crawler options object.\n\n## Reasoning\nA session pool with `maxPoolSize: 5` allows up to 5 distinct browser sessions (each with a unique Camoufox fingerprint). This rotates the fingerprint on retries and across crawl rounds, making the crawler appear more human and reducing the chance of IP-based or fingerprint-based blocking.\n\n## Implementation Details\n1. Open `src/main.ts`.\n2. Locate the `new PlaywrightCrawler({ ... })` options object (around line 75–105).\n3. Add the two properties inside the object, for example right after `maxRequestsPerCrawl,`:\n   ```ts\n   useSessionPool: true,\n   sessionPoolOptions: { maxPoolSize: 5 },\n   ```\n4. Do not change any other existing options.\n5. Verify the file still compiles (`npm run build`) and passes lint (`npm run lint`).\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n- If `useSessionPool` is set to `true` but `sessionPoolOptions` is omitted, Crawlee uses default `maxPoolSize: 1000` which is too large for limited proxy. Our explicit `maxPoolSize: 5` prevents resource overuse.\n- If the crawler is running with a proxy, session rotation may cause IP changes per session – that’s desired.\n- No validation needed; both properties are typed and will be caught by TypeScript if mistyped.\n\n## Validation\n- Run `npm run build` to ensure no TypeScript errors.\n- Run `npm test` to ensure the integration test still passes (the test creates a crawler without these options; it should remain unaffected, though future steps will align test config).\n- Optionally run `apify run` locally and watch logs for session rotation messages (if logging enabled).\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n- This step depends on nothing else; other steps (retry configuration) will rely on the session pool being present.\n- The existing `main.ts` is the only file to change.\n\n## Constraints\n- Do not modify `src/routes.ts`, tests, or input schema in this step.\n- Maintain existing code style (ESM imports with `.js` extension, logging with `apify/log`).\n- The session pool must be configured before any retry logic or post-navigation hooks that might rely on it.\n4. **Set maxConcurrency 1-2 and maxRequestRetries 3**: ## Goal\nAdd `maxConcurrency` (set to 1) and `maxRequestRetries` (set to 3) to the PlaywrightCrawler options in `src/main.ts`.\n\n## Task Type\nModify existing code: update the crawler configuration object.\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\n- `src/main.ts` line ~85–105 contains the crawler instantiation with options such as `proxyConfiguration`, `maxRequestsPerCrawl`, `launchContext`, `preNavigationHooks`, etc.\n- Current options do not include `maxConcurrency` or `maxRequestRetries`; Crawlee defaults are used (concurrency is automatically managed, retries default to 0 or 1 depending on crawler version).\n- The actor uses PlaywrightCrawler from `@crawlee/playwright`.\n- No input schema fields exist yet for these values; they will be hardcoded now and can be exposed later in the optional **extend-input-schema** step.\n\n## Action\nIn `src/main.ts`, locate the object passed to `new PlaywrightCrawler({...})`. Add the following properties:\n- `maxConcurrency: 1` (or 2 if appropriate; use 1 for a more human-like, less aggressive crawl).\n- `maxRequestRetries: 3`.\n\nDo NOT add `useSessionPool` or `sessionPoolOptions`—those belong to a separate step.\n\n## Reasoning\n- `maxConcurrency: 1` reduces parallelism to mimic a single user browsing, preventing detection as a scraper.\n- `maxRequestRetries: 3` ensures transient failures (e.g., timeouts, 5xx) are retried with Crawlee’s built-in exponential backoff, improving robustness without custom logic.\n- Hardcoding is acceptable now; later steps will make these values configurable via input schema if needed.\n\n## Implementation Details\n- Open `src/main.ts`.\n- Find the `new PlaywrightCrawler({` call. Inside the options object, add these lines (order does not matter):\n  ```typescript\n  maxConcurrency: 1,\n  maxRequestRetries: 3,\n  ```\n- Ensure the commas are correct and TypeScript compiles.\n- No other files need modification.\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n- If `maxConcurrency` is set too low for large input lists, the crawl may take longer; this is acceptable for stealth.\n- If `maxRequestRetries` is 3, ensure the `retryOnBlocked` (if used) is not overridden; Crawlee automatically retries on network errors.\n- No special error handling needed—these are simple numeric properties.\n\n## Validation\n- Run `npm run build` (or `npx tsc --noEmit`) to ensure TypeScript compiles.\n- Run the integration test `npx vitest run` to verify the crawler starts and completes with the new settings.\n- Manually inspect that `maxConcurrency` and `maxRequestRetries` appear in the crawler options (e.g., by logging the crawler instance after creation, or checking debug output).\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n- This step depends only on the existing `src/main.ts` file.\n- No new npm dependencies.\n\n## Constraints\n- Do not change `useSessionPool` or any other options not in this step’s scope.\n- Use numeric literals exactly `1` and `3`.\n- Follow existing code style (indentation, commas, etc.).\n- Commit only this change; do not modify tests or input schema.\n5. **Implement proxy rotation on retry with custom error handling**: ## Goal\nEnable automatic proxy rotation on retry attempts within the PlaywrightCrawler, ensuring that each retry uses a different proxy IP from the Apify Proxy pool. Add custom error handling to detect retry-worthy failures (e.g., 403, CAPTCHA, timeout) and force session rotation.\n\n## Task Type\nCode modification – update `src/main.ts` crawler configuration and add a failed request handler.\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\n- Current `src/main.ts` (line ~75-90) creates a `proxyConfiguration` via `Actor.createProxyConfiguration()` but uses it to generate a single proxy URL injected into `launchContext.launchOptions`. This means all requests share the same proxy IP until the browser restarts.\n- Crawlee supports per-request proxy assignment via the `proxyConfiguration` option on the `PlaywrightCrawler`. When set, each request gets a unique proxy URL from the pool, enabling rotation.\n- The session pool (`useSessionPool: true`) can be combined with proxy rotation to further diversify fingerprints.\n- `maxRequestRetries` (set in step `configure-concurrency-retry`) is already defined; retry backoff is built into Crawlee.\n- The existing code does not have a custom `failedRequestHandler` or `errorHandler`.\n- File to modify: `src/main.ts` (around lines 55-105).\n\n## Action\n1. **Remove** the manual proxy URL from `launchOptions` in the `PlaywrightCrawler` config.\n2. **Pass** the existing `proxyConfiguration` object directly to the crawler via the `proxyConfiguration` option (Crawlee will assign a proxy URL per request automatically).\n3. **Add** a `failedRequestHandler` callback to the crawler options. Inside it:\n   - Log the error and the retry count (accessible via `request.retryCount`).\n   - For specific errors (HTTP status >= 400, timeout, network errors), force session rotation by calling `session.retire()` if a session exists on the request (the session pool will create a new session for the next retry).\n4. **Optionally**, set `errorHandler` to catch page-level errors and convert them into retriable errors (e.g., via `throw`).\n\n## Reasoning\n- By using Crawlee’s built-in proxy assignment, every request (including retries) gets a fresh proxy IP, maximizing anti-blocking effectiveness.\n- A custom `failedRequestHandler` allows us to react to specific failure types and trigger session rotation, which is not automatic for non-request errors.\n- This approach avoids extra dependencies and aligns with Crawlee best practices.\n\n## Implementation Details\n### Step-by-step code changes in `src/main.ts`:\n\n**After line ~75** (where `proxyConfiguration` is created), **change crawler instantiation**:\n\n```ts\nconst crawler = new PlaywrightCrawler({\n    proxyConfiguration,  // pass the configuration directly\n    // Remove: launchContext: { launchOptions: { proxy: { server: proxyConfiguration.newUrl() } } },\n    useSessionPool: true,\n    sessionPoolOptions: { maxPoolSize: 5 },\n    maxConcurrency: 1,\n    maxRequestRetries: 3,\n    // ... existing options\n    failedRequestHandler: async ({ request, session, response, error }, crawler) => {\n        log.warning(`Request failed (retry ${request.retryCount}): ${request.url} - ${error?.message || response?.status()}`);\n        // Force session rotation if retryable error\n        if (session && (error || (response && response.status() >= 400))) {\n            session.retire();\n        }\n    },\n    // Keep preNavigationHooks and postNavigationHooks as before\n});\n```\n\n**Note:** The existing `getRandomViewport()` and other launch options remain unchanged in `launchContext`; only proxy URL removal is needed.\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n- If `proxyConfiguration` is undefined (no proxy configured), Crawlee will handle it gracefully (no proxy assigned). Code should check existence before passing?\n- If session is null (e.g., session pool disabled), the `failedRequestHandler` must guard against `session?.retire()`.\n- Errors that are not retriable (e.g., invalid URL) should not rotate session; the handler can check `request.retryCount` to avoid excessive rotation.\n- The `failedRequestHandler` runs after all retries are exhausted; to affect retries, we need to handle errors before the final retry. Crawlee’s retry mechanism is internal; the `errorHandler` (not `failedRequestHandler`) runs on each failure before deciding to retry. So for true per-retry rotation, we should use `errorHandler` instead:\n\n```ts\nerrorHandler: async ({ request, session, response, error }) => {\n    // runs on each failure (before retries are consumed)\n    if (session && (error || (response && response.status() >= 400))) {\n        session.retire();\n    }\n},\n```\n\nUpdate the description to use `errorHandler` for active retry intervention.\n\n## Validation\n- After changes, run `npm run build` and `npm test` (the integration test should still pass).\n- Manually inspect the crawler configuration by logging `crawler.options` to confirm `proxyConfiguration` is set.\n- Optionally, run a test crawl with `maxRequestsPerCrawl: 5` and observe logs to verify that retries trigger session retirement.\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n- Depends on completion of steps `configure-session-pool` (useSessionPool, maxPoolSize) and `configure-concurrency-retry` (maxConcurrency, maxRequestRetries) – the new code references those options.\n- No new npm packages required.\n- Input from the optional `extend-input-schema` step is not needed for this core implementation.\n\n## Constraints\n- Must not break existing proxy functionality for non-retry requests.\n- Must keep the same proxy configuration groups and country (RESIDENTIAL, IT) as set in `Actor.createProxyConfiguration()`.\n- Node.js version >=20, ESM imports, linting rules apply.\n6. **Update integration test to align with new crawler options**: ## Goal\nUpdate `test/main.test.ts` to include the new crawler configuration options (maxConcurrency, maxRequestRetries, useSessionPool, sessionPoolOptions) and any new hooks that were added in previous steps, ensuring the integration test reflects the production behavior while remaining valid and reliable.\n\n## Task Type\nTest file modification (TypeScript, vitest)\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\n- File: `test/main.test.ts` (~30 lines)\n- Current test creates a PlaywrightCrawler with:\n  - `maxRequestsPerCrawl: 10`\n  - `proxyConfiguration` (optional, based on `test.proxy` env var)\n  - `launchContext` with `launchOptions`\n  - `preNavigationHooks` (only the tracker-blocking hook from production)\n  - Uses `Actor.init()` and `Actor.exit()`\n  - Crawls `https://apify.com/` and verifies at least 4 dataset items\n- Production `src/main.ts` now uses:\n  - `maxConcurrency: 2`\n  - `maxRequestRetries: 3`\n  - `useSessionPool: true`\n  - `sessionPoolOptions: { maxPoolSize: 5 }`\n  - Extended `preNavigationHooks` (random delay, cookie consent)\n  - New `postNavigationHooks` (progressive scroll, mouse emulation, wait)\n- The test must stay fast and deterministic; adding retries and concurrency may increase runtime. Use a minimal configuration that still validates the new options are wired correctly.\n\n## Action\n1. Open `test/main.test.ts`\n2. Add the following options to the `PlaywrightCrawler` constructor:\n   - `maxConcurrency: 2`\n   - `maxRequestRetries: 3`\n   - `useSessionPool: true`\n   - `sessionPoolOptions: { maxPoolSize: 5 }`\n3. Update `preNavigationHooks` to include the new delay logic (page.waitForTimeout with random value between 1000-4000) and cookie consent script (page.evaluate to set consent cookie). Use a simplified version that does not require external consent libraries, e.g., evaluate a small cookie-setting snippet.\n4. Add `postNavigationHooks` with:\n   - Progressive scroll: `page.evaluate` to scroll document body in 10 steps, 300ms per step\n   - Mouse emulation: `page.mouse.move(x, y)` with random coordinates\n   - Wait: `page.waitForTimeout(2000 + Math.random() * 3000)`\n5. Ensure the test still waits for `Dataset.open()` and checks `dataset.length >= 4`.\n6. Run `npm test` to confirm the updated test passes.\n\n## Reasoning\n- The test must reflect the production crawler configuration to catch regressions.\n- Adding the new hooks and options ensures that any unexpected side effects (e.g., slower crawling, session rotation errors) are caught early.\n- The test's maxRequestsPerCrawl is kept at 10 to limit runtime; retries won't trigger often on the test URL.\n- The simplified cookie consent script avoids external dependencies and mimics the production behavior.\n\n## Implementation Details\n```typescript\n// In test/main.test.ts, inside the crawler creation block (around line 15-20)\nconst crawler = new PlaywrightCrawler({\n    maxRequestsPerCrawl: 10,\n    maxConcurrency: 2,\n    maxRequestRetries: 3,\n    useSessionPool: true,\n    sessionPoolOptions: { maxPoolSize: 5 },\n    proxyConfiguration: process.env.TEST_PROXY\n        ? await Actor.createProxyConfiguration({ useApifyProxy: true })\n        : undefined,\n    launchContext: {\n        launchOptions: {\n            headless: true,\n        },\n    },\n    preNavigationHooks: [\n        async ({ page }) => {\n            // Random delay 1-4s\n            await page.waitForTimeout(1000 + Math.random() * 3000);\n            // Set a generic cookie consent (pretend user accepted all)\n            await page.evaluate(() => {\n                document.cookie = 'cookie_consent=accepted; path=/; max-age=31536000';\n            });\n        },\n    ],\n    postNavigationHooks: [\n        async ({ page }) => {\n            // Progressive scroll\n            const scrollHeight = await page.evaluate(() => document.body.scrollHeight);\n            const step = scrollHeight / 10;\n            for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {\n                await page.evaluate((y) => window.scrollTo(0, y), step * (i + 1));\n                await page.waitForTimeout(300);\n            }\n            // Mouse move\n            const width = await page.evaluate(() => window.innerWidth);\n            const height = await page.evaluate(() => window.innerHeight);\n            await page.mouse.move(Math.random() * width, Math.random() * height);\n            // Reading delay\n            await page.waitForTimeout(2000 + Math.random() * 3000);\n        },\n    ],\n});\n// Ensure the requestHandler and subsequent dataset check remain unchanged.\n```\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n- If the test times out (default vitest timeout 5000ms), increase timeout to 60000ms with `test.setTimeout(60000)` in the vitest config or inside the test file.\n- If the crawler fails due to session pool exhaustion (unlikely with maxPoolSize 5 and maxConcurrency 2), it will fall back to retries. The test should still pass within 3 retries.\n- The random delay and wait times may cause the test to run slower but should still complete within a reasonable window.\n- Ensure the test does not rely on exact number of dataset items (>=4 is fine).\n\n## Validation\n- Run `npm test` and verify all tests pass.\n- Run `npm run lint` to ensure no linting errors from the new code.\n- Confirm that the test output shows dataset items count >= 4 and that no errors are thrown.\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n- Dependencies: `vitest`, `@crawlee/playwright`, `apify` (already in project).\n- Inputs: None. The test is self-contained.\n- This step depends on the previous steps that implemented the new hooks and configuration options. If those steps are not complete, this test may reference symbols that don't exist yet.\n\n## Constraints\n- Do not change the core logic of the test (crawl Apify.com, verify dataset).\n- Keep the test running time under 60 seconds.\n- Do not add any new npm dependencies.\n- Follow the existing code style (ESM imports with `.js` extension, etc.).\n7. **Extend input schema with maxConcurrency, maxRequestRetries, maxPoolSize (optional)**: ## Goal\nExtend the Actor's input schema (`.actor/input_schema.json`) to expose three new optional configuration parameters: `maxConcurrency`, `maxRequestRetries`, and `maxPoolSize`. This allows users to control concurrency, retry count, and session pool size directly from the Apify UI or API without modifying the source code.\n\n## Task Type\nSchema extension – modify an existing JSON input schema file to add new optional fields with appropriate editors, types, and defaults.\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\nThe Actor's input schema is defined in `.actor/input_schema.json` (located at project root). Currently, it contains two fields:\n- `startUrls` (type: requestListSources, editor: requestListSources)\n- `maxRequestsPerCrawl` (type: integer, default: 100, optional: true)\n\nThe schema conforms to the [Apify input schema specification](https://docs.apify.com/platform/actors/development/input-schema).\n\nThe existing `src/main.ts` code reads these inputs via `Actor.getInput<Input>()` and uses a TypeScript interface (likely defined in `src/main.ts` or a separate types file). The interface must be updated to include the new optional fields.\n\n## Action\n1. Add three new fields to `.actor/input_schema.json` after the `maxRequestsPerCrawl` field:\n   - `maxConcurrency` (integer, optional, default 1, editor: number slider)\n   - `maxRequestRetries` (integer, optional, default 3, editor: number slider)\n   - `maxPoolSize` (integer, optional, default 5, editor: number slider)\n2. Update the TypeScript `Input` interface in `src/main.ts` (or wherever defined) to include these fields as optional numbers.\n3. In `src/main.ts`, after `Actor.getInput<Input>()`, assign default values for these fields when not provided by input, using the same defaults as in the schema (1, 3, 5).\n4. Pass these values to the `PlaywrightCrawler` options:\n   - `maxConcurrency`\n   - `maxRequestRetries` (property of `PlaywrightCrawler`)\n   - `useSessionPool: true` and `sessionPoolOptions: { maxPoolSize }`\n\n## Reasoning\n- Exposing these parameters gives users control over crawling behavior without requiring code changes.\n- Defaults match the hardcoded values planned in the previous steps (concurrency 1, retries 3, pool size 5).\n- The input schema is the standard mechanism for Apify Actor configuration; extending it is the correct architectural choice.\n- The TypeScript interface must be updated to provide type safety and IDE autocompletion.\n\n## Implementation Details\n### File: `.actor/input_schema.json`\nAdd after line 17 (the closing of `maxRequestsPerCrawl`):\n```json\n,\n{\n    \"key\": \"maxConcurrency\",\n    \"type\": \"integer\",\n    \"title\": \"Max Concurrency\",\n    \"description\": \"Maximum number of concurrent browser pages (1-10). Lower values appear more human-like.\",\n    \"default\": 1,\n    \"minimum\": 1,\n    \"maximum\": 10,\n    \"editor\": \"number\",\n    \"optional\": true\n},\n{\n    \"key\": \"maxRequestRetries\",\n    \"type\": \"integer\",\n    \"title\": \"Max Request Retries\",\n    \"description\": \"Number of retries for failed requests (exponential backoff).\",\n    \"default\": 3,\n    \"minimum\": 0,\n    \"maximum\": 5,\n    \"editor\": \"number\",\n    \"optional\": true\n},\n{\n    \"key\": \"maxPoolSize\",\n    \"type\": \"integer\",\n    \"title\": \"Max Session Pool Size\",\n    \"description\": \"Maximum number of browser sessions to rotate (each session has a different fingerprint).\",\n    \"default\": 5,\n    \"minimum\": 1,\n    \"maximum\": 10,\n    \"editor\": \"number\",\n    \"optional\": true\n}\n```\n\n### File: `src/main.ts`\nUpdate the Input interface (likely around line 7-12):\n```typescript\ninterface Input {\n    startUrls?: RequestListTypes.Request[];\n    maxRequestsPerCrawl?: number;\n    maxConcurrency?: number;\n    maxRequestRetries?: number;\n    maxPoolSize?: number;\n}\n```\n\nAfter input retrieval (around line 20-25):\n```typescript\nconst input = await Actor.getInput<Input>() ?? {};\nconst maxConcurrency = input.maxConcurrency ?? 1;\nconst maxRequestRetries = input.maxRequestRetries ?? 3;\nconst maxPoolSize = input.maxPoolSize ?? 5;\n```\n\nPass these values to the crawler constructor options (around line 50-70):\n```typescript\nnew PlaywrightCrawler({\n    ...\n    useSessionPool: true,\n    sessionPoolOptions: { maxPoolSize },\n    maxConcurrency,\n    maxRequestRetries,\n    ...\n})\n```\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n- If user provides values outside min/max, Apify SDK will enforce schema validation and show error in UI.\n- `maxConcurrency` of 0 should be handled by schema `minimum:1`; no extra code needed.\n- If `maxRequestRetries` is set to 0, no retries will occur; this is acceptable.\n- Ensure that when `useSessionPool` is already set to true elsewhere, the `sessionPoolOptions` override is correct.\n\n## Validation\n1. Run `apify run` with input that only contains `startUrls` – defaults should be applied.\n2. Run with explicit values for all three fields – verify they are used.\n3. Check the Apify UI schema preview in local dev (if available) to ensure new fields render correctly.\n4. Ensure no TypeScript errors: `npm run build` must pass.\n5. Run integration test: `npm test` – it should still pass (test may use defaults).\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n- **Dependencies**: This step depends on `configure-concurrency-retry` (which defined the hardcoded values). The input schema must align with those defaults.\n- **Inputs**: Existing `.actor/input_schema.json`, `src/main.ts` (Input interface and crawler construction).\n\n## Constraints\n- Must not break backward compatibility: all new fields are optional.\n- Defaults must match the values used in the `configure-concurrency-retry` step (maxConcurrency=1, maxRequestRetries=3, maxPoolSize=5).\n- The schema JSON must be valid according to Apify input schema spec.\n- No new npm dependencies required.\n\n## API and Integration Impact\n- Changes are internal to actor schema and source; no external API changes.\n- Users calling the actor via Apify API can now include these parameters in the input body.\n\n## Documentation Impact\n- If a README or actor documentation exists, it should be updated to mention the new configurable parameters. However, the Apify UI will auto-generate documentation from the schema.\n\n## Diagram\n(Not applicable)",
